      With Twitter in tatters, I've realized I need to get my web presence back into shape. This site is a continual work in progress. Right now, I've been mostly writing at least twice a month in my <strong><a href="https://ronbronson.substack.com/">long-dormant music newsletter</a></strong>. I've been an intermittent critic since the early days of the web, but these days, I'm mostly writing about observations and sharing playlists. <br> </p>

     <p> Lately, I've been working on a bevy of locally-focused projects including two public design exhibitions. In May, my show <strong><a href="https://www.ronbronson.design/posts/parliament-of-neighbors">"A Parliament of Neighbors"</a></strong> debuted at an experimental art gallery hosted at a Portland mall. Last fall, I organized a public design exhibit called <strong><a href="https://www.ronbronson.design/posts/designers-share">The Designer's Share of the Problem"</a> </strong>for the Portland Design Festival. </p>

<p>I've been organizing my personal activities within a personal studio tentatively named Parallel 57 for a bevy of activities locally including a community of practice for design types, a book club, and other in-person events both in Portland and elsewhere. 

Depending on when you met me, you might be aware of my past lives as a tea swiller, <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tennis_polo">game designer</a></strong> (like of an actual sport), <strong><a href="https://www.ronbronson.design/tennis">tennis coach</a></strong>, or skeeball champion. </p>

